\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that we can write the force as the sum of an enthalpic term and an
 entropic term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}-T\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the Maxwell relation derived previously, along with the data in the
 graph, estimate (numerically) the fraction of the elasticity of the rubber
 (i.e.
 f) that comes from the entropic term.
 Because you’re working with ratios, the distinction between force and modulus
 doesn’t matter ─ the geometrical factors that connect them cancel out.
 Which term (enthalpic or entropic) dominates?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From your result, does the rubber band get warmer or colder when you stretch
 it? When it retracts to its original length? If you have a rubber band
 handy, test your conclusion empirically and report the results.
 (Lips are sensitive differential thermometers.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
