\begin_layout Problem
In this problem you will calculate analytically the vibrational contribution
 to the energy of a diatomic molecule as a function of temperature, and,
 by making suitable approximations, consider the behavior in the low- and
 high-temperature limits.
 Model the molecule quantum mechanically as a particle in a three-dimensional
 infinite square (i.e.
 cubical) well of side length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that is also able to vibrate internally at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Represent the vibrational as a quantum harmonic oscillator.
 The center-of-mass and vibrational degrees of freedom are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What are the quantum numbers that define a microstate of the molecule? What
 is the energy of the microstate in terms of those quantum numbers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 You can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is very large, so that the spacing between center-of-mass states is much
 smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, but do not assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 is small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle U\right\rangle =k_{B}T^{2}\frac{\partial\ln Z}{\partial T}
\]

\end_inset

find the average energy of the molecule at low temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\ll\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Compare your result to what is expected from classical equipartition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find the average energy of the molecule at high temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\gg\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Compare your result to what is expected from classical equipartition.
 
\end_layout

